This paper is primarily focused on a computer vision problem, specifically single image super-resolution, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and their architecture, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a new CNN architecture for the problem, which could also place it in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The paper also discusses the challenges of deep CNNs and proposes solutions, which could place it in the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the results of experiments and comparisons of different residual architectures, which could place it in the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category.
